INSERT INTO collect_news (url, body, headline, author, datetime, current) SELECT * FROM ( SELECT 'http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/e94e9878-33c0-11df-8b99-00144feabdc0.html', 'When Allan Zeman became chairman of Hong Kong''s Ocean Park in 2003, he took over the running of a weather-beaten business on the brink of bankruptcy. That same year, Disney also began construction in Hong Kong of its first theme park on Chinese soil, presenting the biggest threat to the home-grown park since it was founded in 1977.</p>
Seven years later, Mr Zeman, a leisure industry veteran known for developing the city''s Lan Kwai Fong bar area, has managed to defy the doubters.</p>
Mainland Chinese visitors to Ocean Park and its trademark dolphin shows have been steadily increasing, while Disney''s cartoon characters have struggled to win them over.</p>
In January this year, Hong Kong Disneyland disclosed its financial details for the first time, revealing a net loss of HK$1.3bn in its last financial year. Although attendance rose slightly to 4.6m in the year to October 3, 2009, it was far short of its original projection of up to 5.6m visitors annually.</p>
By contrast, Ocean Park received 4.8m people in the 12 months to June 2009 and reported a net profit of HK$98.6m. Back in 2003, its attendance was 2.9m and it made a net loss of HK$4.1m.</p>
"We couldn''t compete against Disney with the money they had. We needed to find a way to make us relevant," says Mr Zeman.</p>
"The first thing we realised was that Ocean Park was a local park with local brand awareness."</p>
With that in mind, it began a series of special events during popular festivals such as Chinese New Year and Halloween. It also drew up a HK$5.6bn (US$715m) redevelopment plan that would double the number of shows and rides by 2013, build three on-site hotels and distinguish itself from other theme parks by expanding its animal collection.</p>
"Understanding the culture and coming with the events that are relevant to the local culture is our strength," says Mr Zeman, in the park''s Panda Cafe.</p>
When Disney opened its Hong Kong magic kingdom in 2005, Mr Zeman was prepared for a huge drop in attendance.</p>
Many tourists from mainland China, which since 2004 had become a major source of visitors to Hong Kong, timed their holidays that year to catch the launch of Disneyland.</p>
But due to marketing glitches and complaints about its small size, Hong Kong Disneyland has failed to become the intimidating rival that Ocean Park once feared.</p>
While the tale of a home-grown theme park beating an internationally known name is spectacular, the success of Ocean Park is also unusual as it is not controlled by a cash-rich conglomerate, but wholly-owned by the government.</p>
